<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-578-191  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 578 191.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  May 8 1989 v10 n19 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Companies see growing DEC utilities market. (Digital EquipmentCorp VAX computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mahnke, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software vendors state that the market for DEC utilities hasbecome big enough to attract the financing and management talentnecessary to build large third-party businesses offering a widerange of programs and service.andP;  Utility vendor Demax Software Incstates that the DEC system software market could grow from $35million to $1.2 billion by 1992.andP;  A DEC analyst disputes thisclaim, saying that because DEC's VMS system software includes somany built-in tools, the need for third-party tools is minimal.andP;  Asurvey of 10,300 VAX sites seems to confirm this, revealing thatDEC users generally have only modest plans to acquire more systemsoftware.andP;  Areas of VMS that could be improved include managinglarge disk farms, storage hierarchies and data set migration; andenabling better control of both software releases and multiplesimultaneous applications across a network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (standards).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   VMS (Operating system) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Utility ProgramsCompatible SoftwareGrowthIndustry AnalysisSoftware PublishersApplicationsThird-Party Vendors.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Software utilities for Vaxes. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>